{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11403"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.29,0.11,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110287"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92558"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42589"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110287"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department overnight with a one-hour history of sudden onset chest pain. The pain is \u0027tearing\u0027 in character, felt in the anterior chest, and is currently 10/10 in severity. It is associated with dizziness and shortness of breath. He has a medical history of hypertension, bicuspid aortic valve, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include amlodipine and tiotropium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 109/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is a pulse deficit in both femoral arteries. Auscultation of the praecordium reveals an early diastolic decrescendo murmur heard maximally along the right sternal border. An electrocardiogram shows sinus tachycardia but is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Cardiac troponin","Transoesophageal echocardiogram","Invasive aortography","CT aortography"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of an acute aortic dissection, specifically a Stanford Type A dissection involving the ascending aorta. The key features supporting this diagnosis are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Sudden onset of severe, \u0027tearing\u0027 chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. History of hypertension and bicuspid aortic valve (a high-risk condition for aortic dissection).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Haemodynamic instability (low blood pressure, tachycardia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Pulse deficit in both femoral arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5. New diastolic murmur suggestive of acute aortic regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT aortography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation. It is an excellent test for diagnosing aortic dissection and is often the test of choice in the emergency department. However, it is important to first stabilise the patient as much as possible prior, as transport to CT can be a high risk period for deterioration outside of the resuscitation area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E might show a widened mediastinum in aortic dissection, but it is neither sensitive nor specific enough for diagnosis. It would delay definitive diagnosis in this critical situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac troponin\u003C/strong\u003E are useful for diagnosing myocardial infarction, but they are not the most appropriate test for suspected aortic dissection. While aortic dissection can sometimes cause coronary artery involvement and subsequent myocardial ischaemia, troponin testing would not provide the definitive diagnosis needed in this emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransoesophageal echocardiogram (TOE)\u003C/strong\u003E can quickly provide high-quality images of the ascending aorta, aortic arch, and descending thoracic aorta, allowing for reliable diagnosis. It can be performed at the bedside and provides real-time images. However, in order to facilitate this, the patient must be sedated, a clinician capable of performing the procedure available, as well as access to equipment. Although this may be a great option in the haemodynamically unstable patient, it is most often not a viable option and is highly operator dependent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvasive Aortogram\u003C/strong\u003E has largely been superseded by CT angiography for the evaluation of aortic dissection due to its invasive nature and low sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while several imaging modalities can diagnose aortic dissection, CT aortography is the most commonly utilised in the Emergency Department due to availability and access. Transoesophageal echocardiogram in theory is an excellent option in patients with high clinical suspicion for acute Type A aortic dissection, however logistically this is more often not plausible due to lack of availability of skilled technicians, requirement for sedation, and equipment availability, especially in this scenario occurring overnight.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tearing chest pain in an older patient should always raise the possibility of aortic dissection.","CT aortography is often the imaging modality of choice in these patients given transoesophageal echocardiogram is a resource heavy investigation, and often not a plausible option.","CT aortography can also provide additional details such as the details such as the anatomy of the dissection and location of the dissection flap, flap extension into the great vessels, and signs of aortic rupture.","Bicuspid aortic valve is a high-risk condition associated with aortic dissection."],"references":["2022 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Aortic Disease: A Report of the American Heart Association/American College of Cardiology Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines","Nienaber CA, Clough RA. Management of acute aortic dissection. Lancet 2015; 385:800-11. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25662791/","Tintinalli JE, Ma OJ, Yealy DM, Meckler GD, Stapczynski JS, Cline DM, Thomas SH, editors. Tintinalli\u2019s emergency medicine: a comprehensive study guide. 9th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Education; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92558"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1